{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521473"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13658"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13658"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.55,0.02,0.03,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6263"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52744"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6263"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-04-27T12:03:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T14:00:45+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-09-04T14:02:09+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-29 03:02:28"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13658"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5808"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42903"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38118"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52744"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent complaining of increasing shortness of breath, chest pain, and fatigue over the past year. He has a medical history of Downs syndrome and a congenital heart defect diagnosed in childhood. He has lived abroad with his family for many years and has not had regular follow-up. His family history is significant for ischaemic heart disease. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 85% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is cyanotic with clubbing of the fingers and toes. Auscultation reveals a loud second heart sound and a holosystolic murmur. An echocardiogram shows right ventricular hypertrophy, a ventricular septal defect with right-to-left shunt, and increased pulmonary artery pressures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patent ductus arteriosus","Eisenmenger syndrome","Persistent truncus arteriosus","Primary pulmonary hypertension","Tetralogy of Fallot"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms of increasing shortness of breath, chest pain, fatigue, cyanosis, and digital clubbing, combined with his history of a congenital heart defect and Down syndrome, and findings on examination and echocardiography, suggest the development of \u003Cstrong\u003EEisenmenger syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This syndrome occurs when a long-standing left-to-right shunt caused by a congenital heart defect leads to pulmonary hypertension and eventually a reversal of the shunt to a right-to-left direction. The patient\u0027s echocardiogram findings of right ventricular hypertrophy, a ventricular septal defect with right-to-left shunt, and increased pulmonary artery pressures confirm this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEisenmenger syndrome leads to symptoms such as cyanosis, digital clubbing, and polycythemia. Management focuses on treating pulmonary hypertension and monitoring for complications. Regular follow-up for congenital heart defects is crucial to prevent progression to Eisenmenger syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatent ductus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E (PDA) can cause symptoms of shortness of breath and fatigue due to left-to-right shunting, leading to right heart enlargement and eventually right heart failure. It is associated with a murmur throughout diastole and systole. The quality of the murmur is referred to as \u0022machinery-like\u0022 due to the high turbulence created from the shunt. It is a significant congenital heart disease that warrants close monitoring and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistent truncus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in infancy with symptoms of heart failure and cyanosis due to a single arterial trunk arising from the heart. It is usually diagnosed and managed early in life, and would not present in adulthood with the symptoms described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary pulmonary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E can cause similar symptoms of shortness of breath and fatigue, however would not involve a history of congenital heart defects or echocardiographic findings of a ventricular septal defect and right-to-left shunt. The presence of these findings is crucial for diagnosing Eisenmenger syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetralogy of Fallot\u003C/strong\u003E is a cyanotic heart defect that consists of four features: a ventricular septal defect, pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, and an overriding aorta. It is usually diagnosed and surgically corrected in childhood. Untreated cases can lead to severe cyanosis, digital clubbing, and polycythemia, but the presentation of Eisenmenger syndrome with its specific echocardiographic findings and history is more indicative of the progression of an uncorrected left-to-right shunt rather than untreated Tetralogy of Fallot.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Eisenmenger syndrome is a complication of uncorrected left-to-right shunts that lead to pulmonary hypertension and shunt reversal.","Symptoms of Eisenmenger syndrome include cyanosis, digital clubbing, and chest pain, with echocardiographic findings of right ventricular hypertrophy and increased pulmonary artery pressures."],"references":["Arvanitaki A, Giannakoulas G, Baumgartner H, Lammers AE. Eisenmenger syndrome: diagnosis, prognosis and clinical management. Heart. 2020 Nov 1;106(21):1638-45. Available at: https://heart.bmj.com/content/106/21/1638.abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13658"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T14:00:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T14:02:01+09:30","number":8,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-09-09T14:00:58+09:30","plagiarismScore":5.1,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-6263-8.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T050453Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=1fab483707b9d8df438ba72c1f5